  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Naples who spent much of her life navigating the world with a deep sense of anxiety and a commitment to understanding human behavior through both personal experience and observation, I believe stereotype threat in STEM is a real and deeply felt phenomenon that needs careful, compassionate attention. Growing up in a time when education was often a path to opportunity but not always a guarantee of success, I witnessed firsthand how stereotypes about gender and ethnicity could shape expectations and self-perception. In my upper secondary education, I was encouraged to pursue science and math, but I also remember the quiet moments of doubt when I saw classmates who were girls or immigrants struggling with the same subjects. Stereotype threat—the fear of confirming negative stereotypes about one's group—can make students feel like they are failing not because of lack of ability, but because of their identity. This is especially true in STEM fields where women and minorities have historically been underrepresented. I think we must address it, but not with top-down mandates that might overwhelm those already feeling anxious. Instead, we should foster environments where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of judgment. For example, in my community, we have local workshops where people of all ages come together to learn about science through hands-on activities, and I’ve seen how these spaces can build confidence. It’s important to recognize that change isn’t about fixing people but about creating inclusive spaces where everyone can thrive. In a world that often feels chaotic and uncertain, this kind of support is not just helpful—it’s essential.",
